</table>
<p><a href="G%C3%A9rard_Houllier" title="Gérard Houllier">Gérard Houllier</a>, the former <a href="France_national_football_team" title="France national football team">French</a> national coach, was drafted into the Liverpool management team for the 1998–99 season to work alongside <a href="Roy_Evans" title="Roy Evans">Roy Evans</a>. After a promising start, results took a turn for the worse and Evans found that the partnership did not suit him. He quit that November after a lacklustre 3-1 Worthington's Cup defeat to Tottenham, with Liverpool in the bottom half of the league. Houllier's reign as sole manager began with a 3-1 defeat to Leeds United, with his first win attained against Aston Villa by dint of a 4-2 win, aided by a Robbie Fowler hat-trick. Shortly afterwards, he handed a debut to 18-year old midfielder <a href="Steven_Gerrard" title="Steven Gerrard">Steven Gerrard</a>. A major followed when Steve McManaman announced he was leaving the club on a Bosman free transfer to join Real Madrid. Liverpool's form remained inconsistent and at the end of the season Liverpool finished a disappointing seventh – not even enough for a <a href="UEFA_Cup" title="UEFA Cup" class="mw-redirect">UEFA Cup</a> place.</p>
<p>Houllier performed major squad surgery during the summer of 1999, with a number of players leaving the club. The most notable departures included goalkeeper David James, who joined Aston Villa, and captain Paul Ince, who was unimpressed by Houllier's regime and was sold to Middlesbrough for £1 million. Houllier earmarked the Liverpool defence as an area for improvement, which led to the signings of centre-backs <a href="Sami_Hyypi%C3%A4" title="Sami Hyypiä">Sami Hyypiä</a> and <a href="Stephane_Henchoz" title="Stephane Henchoz" class="mw-redirect">Stephane Henchoz</a> and Newcastle's defensive midfielder <a href="Dietmar_Hamann" title="Dietmar Hamann">Dietmar Hamann</a>, while Dutch goalkeeper <a href="Sander_Westerveld" title="Sander Westerveld">Sander Westerveld</a> was signed to replace James. He also signed Czech midfielder <a href="Vladimir_Smicer" title="Vladimir Smicer" class="mw-redirect">Vladimir Smicer</a> and Guinea forward <a href="Titi_Camara" title="Titi Camara">Titi Camara</a>. Long-serving midfielder Jamie Redknapp became club captain. After a stuttering start, including a shock home defeat to newly promoted <a href="Watford_F.C." title="Watford F.C.">Watford F.C.</a>, Liverpool went on a strong mid-season run which saw the team lose just two matches in 26 and climb to third in the table by spring. With Fowler and Owen affected by injuries, Liverpool signed Leicester forward <a href="Emile_Heskey" title="Emile Heskey">Emile Heskey</a> in March for a new club record fee of £11 million. At this point, Liverpool were in a strong position to qualify for the lucrative UEFA Champions League for the first time, but ended the season poorly, failing to score and picking up just two points from their last five matches and the side ended fourth, instead having to settle for a UEFA Cup place. Some consolation lay in the team's defensive record, with only 30 goals conceded all campaign, the lowest in the top flight.</p>
<p>During the summer of 2000, Liverpool signed Bayern Munich defender <a href="Markus_Babbel" title="Markus Babbel">Markus Babbel</a> on a free transfer. Houllier then infuriated Everton supporters by signing their England international midfielder <a href="Nick_Barmby" title="Nick Barmby">Nick Barmby</a> for £6 million, who became the first player to move directly from Everton to Liverpool since 1959. German wing-back <a href="Christian_Ziege" title="Christian Ziege">Christian Ziege</a> joined in an equally controversial £5.5 million transfer from Middlesbrough.</p>
<p>Off of the pitch, September 2000 saw Liverpool become one of the founder members of the <a href="G-14" title="G-14">G-14</a> group of clubs, an organisation formed to provide a united voice for major European football clubs in negotiations with FIFA and UEFA. Liverpool would remain a member of the G-14 until its disbandment in 2008 when it was replaced by the <a href="European_Club_Association" title="European Club Association">European Club Association</a> which Liverpool subsequently joined.</p>
<p>2000–01 was Liverpool's best season for many years. The likes of <a href="Michael_Owen" title="Michael Owen">Owen</a>, <a href="Robbie_Fowler" title="Robbie Fowler">Fowler</a>, <a href="Steven_Gerrard" title="Steven Gerrard">Gerrard</a> and <a href="Sami_Hyypi%C3%A4" title="Sami Hyypiä">Hyypiä</a> contributed to the club's third place in the Premiership (thus qualifying for the Champions League) as well winning the FA Cup, League Cup and UEFA Cup, followed by the <a href="FA_Community_Shield" title="FA Community Shield">Charity Shield</a> and <a href="European_Super_Cup" title="European Super Cup" class="mw-redirect">European Super Cup</a> later in 2001. The League Cup was won by beating <a href="Birmingham_City_F.C." title="Birmingham City F.C.">Birmingham City</a> on penalties after a 1–1 draw, the FA Cup by beating <a href="Arsenal_F.C." title="Arsenal F.C.">Arsenal</a> 2–1 with two goals from <a href="Michael_Owen" title="Michael Owen">Michael Owen</a> in the last ten minutes and the UEFA Cup by beating <a href="Deportivo_Alav%C3%A9s" title="Deportivo Alavés">Alavés</a>, in an extraordinary game, 5–4 in extra time.</p>
<p>Liverpool began the 2001-02 season by beating Manchester United 2-1 to win the Charity Shield, and winning a fifth trophy of the calendar year with a 3–2 victory against Champions League winners Bayern Munich in the European Super Cup. They also confirmed their qualification to the Champions League group stages by defeating Finnish side F.C. Haka 9–1 on aggregate at the third qualifying stage. The summer transfer activity was quiet, with Norwegian full-back <a href="John_Arne_Riise" title="John Arne Riise">John Arne Riise</a> joining to replace the Tottenham-bound Ziege. However, after a costly mistake which led to a shock defeat to Bolton Wanderers, Houllier axed Westerveld and sanctioned the signings of two new goalkeepers, Feyenoord's <a href="Jerzy_Dudek" title="Jerzy Dudek">Jerzy Dudek</a> and Coventry's <a href="Chris_Kirkland" title="Chris Kirkland">Chris Kirkland</a>.</p>
<p>Liverpool finished Premiership runners-up in <a href="2001-02_FA_Premier_League" title="2001-02 FA Premier League" class="mw-redirect">2001–02</a>, their best league finish since 1991, but suffered a humiliating defeat in the <a href="Football_League_Cup" title="Football League Cup">League Cup</a> Third Round at the hands of <a href="Grimsby_Town_F.C." title="Grimsby Town F.C.">Grimsby Town</a>. 2001 was also dramatic for Houllier personally as he suffered a major heart problem in the October league match against Leeds, which required major surgery and prevented him from returning to the dugout until March 2002. In his absence, Houllier's replacement Phil Thompson maintained the club's title challenge, although many Liverpool fans were upset by the decision to sell Robbie Fowler to Leeds in November 2001. Liverpool's first Champions League campaign was ended at the quarter-final stage by German side (and eventual runners-up) Bayer Leverkusen, who defeated the Reds 4–3 on aggregate.</p>
<p>Liverpool won another League Cup in <a href="2002%E2%80%9303_Football_League_Cup" title="2002–03 Football League Cup">2003</a>, with a 2–0 victory over Manchester United, but the league campaign was a disappointment. After a good start, which saw the Reds top the table in November 2002, the team did not win a league match for another two months - their longest streak of not winning any games in the top flight - during which time the team fell as low as seventh in the table. Eventually, the team finished fifth after a final day defeat at Chelsea, leading to the club missing out on Champions League football for the following campaign. Houllier's transfer activity in the summer of 2002 was criticised, with <a href="El-Hadji_Diouf" title="El-Hadji Diouf" class="mw-redirect">El-Hadji Diouf</a>, <a href="Salif_Diao" title="Salif Diao">Salif Diao</a> and <a href="Bruno_Cheyrou" title="Bruno Cheyrou">Bruno Cheyrou</a> all disappointing. Despite the signings of <a href="Harry_Kewell" title="Harry Kewell">Harry Kewell</a> and <a href="Steve_Finnan" title="Steve Finnan">Steve Finnan</a>, in <a href="2003%E2%80%9304_in_English_football" title="2003–04 in English football">2003–04</a> Houllier came no closer to winning the league title, in fact finishing thirty points behind the champions Arsenal. Although Liverpool qualified for the <a href="UEFA_Champions_League" title="UEFA Champions League">Champions League</a> by finishing fourth (making three qualifications during his tenure), fans saw Houllier's conservative and defensive tactics as sacrificing too much attacking impetus to challenge Arsenal and Manchester United for the title, and pointed to disappointing results such as a 2–1 reverse at home to Southampton in December 2003. Against a background of growing disquiet amongst the Liverpool supporters, Houllier was dismissed on 24 May 2004 and subsequently replaced by the <a href="Spain" title="Spain">Spaniard</a> <a href="Rafael_Ben%C3%ADtez" title="Rafael Benítez">Rafael Benítez</a> who had just guided <a href="Valencia_C.F." title="Valencia C.F." class="mw-redirect">Valencia</a> to the <a href="La_Liga" title="La Liga">Spanish league</a> title and UEFA Cup.</p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=History_of_Liverpool_F.C.&action=edit&section=14.php.html" title="Edit section: The Rafael Benítez era (2004–2010)">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="The_Rafael_Ben.C3.ADtez_era_.282004.E2.80.932010.29">The Rafael Benítez era (2004–2010)</span></h2>
<p><i>Honours won: UEFA Champions League (2005), UEFA Super Cup (2005), FA Cup (2006), FA Community Shield (2006)</i></p>
<p><i>Runner-up: League Cup (2005), Champions League (2007), Club World Cup (2005), Premier League (2009)</i></p>
<table style="float: right; width: 160px; border: #99B3FF solid 1px">
